    "narrative": "For today\u2019s slate, **Lawrence Butler** and **Jos\u00e9 Ram\u00edrez** stand out as the pillars of the LawDog lineup. **Lawrence Butler** projects as our premier play at a 73.47 score; he draws a favorable matchup against Fedde (xERA 5.60) and benefits from a significant 10% park boost, making him an ideal candidate to capitalize on the weak opposing starter. Similarly, **Jos\u00e9 Ram\u00edrez** offers a high-floor, high-ceiling option (70.30) against Kremer. While both face right-handed pitching, their overall talent profiles and favorable order positions render them must-starts despite slight negative platoon adjustments in our model. **Luis Arraez** and **Matt Chapman** also command respect today, both exceeding the 60.00 threshold as they look to exploit the 4.09 xERA of Cavalli.\n\nThe most difficult bench decision involved **Jonathan Aranda**, who flirted with a starting spot against Skenes. Although **Jonathan Aranda** maintains an impressive xwOBA of 0.382 and a 12% platoon edge, the sheer dominance of the opposing arm\u2014Skenes\u2019 3.10 xERA\u2014deflated his efficiency score to 48.79. We opted for the higher-upside profiles of **Masyn Winn** and **Geraldo Perdomo**, both of whom are nearing the 60.00 mark and offer better volume opportunities in their respective lineups. We are also closely monitoring the bottom of the order; while **Jeremiah Jackson** and **Wenceel Perez** are currently in the lineup, their sub-50 scores leave them on a short leash if game caps become a concern as the day progresses.\n\nRegarding risk, **Cal Raleigh** remains a point of concern; despite his power potential, the combination of Eovaldi\u2019s elite 3.17 xERA and a 5% park penalty has suppressed his score to a marginal 45.17. Furthermore, the 5% wind-in penalty at the stadium negatively impacts both **Gleyber Torres** and **Wenceel Perez**, requiring us to temper expectations for power production from those two spots. We are effectively navigating 